5.1 Project Overview

This project is a multi-process application using pipes (Category 1). The program performs sentiment analysis on input text by distributing sentences across multiple worker processes and collecting their results. The parent process reads text from standard input, splits the input into one or more sentences based on punctuation, and assigns each sentence to a worker process. Each worker computes a sentiment score and sends the result back to the parent through a pipe. In main.c, the parent process creates multiple worker processes using fork() and establishes two pipes per worker for communication. Each worker executes the worker() function, where it waits for input, processes a sentence, and returns a result. Communication is done using fixed-size messages defined by the SentenceMsg and Result structures, which ensures consistent and predictable data transfer between processes.

The program accepts input through standard input. Users can type input interactively or pipe text from another command or file. e.g:

	echo "This is good. This is bad." | ./sentiment -a

In default mode, the program outputs summary statistics such as the total number of sentences analyzed, the number of positive and negative sentences, the average sentiment score, and the overall sentiment. When the -a flag is used, the program prints detailed results for each sentence, including the sentence text, its predicted label, and its score.

The main concepts of the project are process creation, concurrency, and inter-process communication using pipes. The sentiment model serves as the computational task assigned to each worker, while the parent process coordinates task distribution and result collection.



5.2 Build Instructions

The project can be compiled using the Makefile.
To build the project, run the following command:

	make

This compiles all .c files with the flags -Wall -Wextra -g and produces two executables:
sentiment, which is the main program
test, which is a helper program used to test sentiment prediction on a single sentence

The Makefile ensures that all object files are built first and then linked together. It also links the math library using -lm, which is required for functions such as expf() used in model.c.

To run the main program, run:

	./sentiment

The program reads input from standard input. Users can type input manually and press Ctrl+D to signal the end of input, or provide input using a pipe or file redirection. For example:

	echo "This is good. This is bad." | ./sentiment -a

To display detailed results for each sentence, the -a flag can be used:

	./sentiment -a

The test program can be used to evaluate a single sentence:

	./test "this is great”

To remove all compiled files, including object files and executables, run:

	make clean

The program requires the files weights.bin and vocab.bin to be present in the working directory. If these files are missing, the program will fail to load the model in load.c.

